'''Cooper Mountain Nature Park''' is a {{convert|231|acre}} nature park in the [[Portland metropolitan area]] in the U.S. state of [[Oregon]]. Opened in 2009, the park is owned and operated by [[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]], the regional government in the Oregon portion of the metro area.<ref name="prairies">{{cite news|url=http://www.portlandtribune.com/sustainable/story.php?story_id=125002920310763900|title=Nature park restores wildlife, prairies|last=Anderson|first=Jennifer|date=August 13, 2009|work=Sherwood Outlook|publisher=Pamplin Media Group|accessdate=2009-10-19}}</ref> The park is named after [[Cooper Mountain (Oregon)|Cooper Mountain]], the primary geological feature in the area near [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]]. Maintained by the regional [[Tualatin Hills Park & Recreation District]], the natural area has {{convert|3.5|mi}} of hiking trails.<ref name="hike">{{cite news|url=http://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=124595242017825200|title=Take a hike|last=Lent|first=Christina|date=June 25, 2009|work=The Beaverton Valley Times|accessdate=2009-10-19}}</ref>

==History==
[[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] area voters approved a [[bond measure]] in 1995 that provided funding for the purchase of [[Open space reserve|greenspace]]s by Metro.<ref name="stumps">{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/washingtoncounty/index.ssf/2009/06/from_stumps_to_spectacular.html|title=From stumps to spectacular|last=Uno|first=Wesley|date=June 25, 2009|work=[[The Oregonian]]|accessdate=2009-10-20}}</ref> Metro covers most of [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington]], [[Clackamas County, Oregon|Clackamas]], and [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah]] counties in the northwest part of Oregon. Metro began buying land on Cooper Mountain near [[Aloha, Oregon|Aloha]] and Beaverton in 1997, and spent $6.58 million in total on land.<ref name="stumps"/><ref name="argus">{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/argus/index.ssf?/base/news/1241549454194680.xml&coll=6|title=Mountain preserve set to open June 27|date=May 5, 2009 |work=[[The Hillsboro Argus]]|accessdate=2009-10-20}}</ref> Voters approved an additional bond in 2006, and Metro spent almost $2 million from that bond on facilities at Cooper Mountain.<ref name="stumps"/> Metro also received a $500,000 grant from the [[Oregon Department of Parks and Recreation]] and a $40,000 grant from the [[National Fish and Wildlife Foundation]] for development of the park.<ref name="stumps"/> To prepare the area for the park and help restore the native habitat, the area was burned in 2008.<ref name="prairies"/> Cooper Mountain Nature Park opened on June 27, 2009.<ref name="stumps"/><ref name="argus"/> Through 2009, volunteers and Metro planted approximately 100,000 shrubs and trees at the park.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/washingtoncounty/index.ssf/2010/01/park_to_host_saturday_educatio.html|title=Park to host Saturday educational open house|last=Gregory|first=Roger|date=January 20, 2010|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=18 February 2010}}</ref>

==Features==
Cooper Mountain Nature Park is located on the south side of the {{convert|774|ft|adj=on}} tall [[Cooper Mountain (Oregon)|Cooper Mountain]] in eastern Washington County.<ref name="stumps"/><ref name="argus"/><ref>{{Cite gnis| id =1136172 | name =Cooper Mountain| accessdate =2009-10-20 | entrydate =1980-11-28}}</ref> The mountain is a former volcano in the [[Tualatin Valley]].<ref name="stumps"/> The park's natural areas include groves of oak trees, wetlands, prairie, ponds, and forested areas.<ref name="stumps"/> Metro owns the park, but will pay Tualatin Hills Parks and Recreation about $600,000 to maintain the park over a ten-year contract.<ref name="stumps"/> The {{convert|231|acre}} natural area is surrounded by agricultural lands to the south and urban development on the north.<ref name="metro">{{cite web|url=http://www.oregonmetro.gov/index.cfm/go/by.web/id=16016|title=Discover Cooper Mountain Nature Park|publisher=Metro|accessdate=2009-10-20}}</ref> Cooper Mountain is between [[Oregon Route 10]] and [[Oregon Route 210]] south of Beaverton.<ref name="metro"/>
[[File:Cooper Mountain Nature Park tree plantings.JPG|thumb|Trail and young trees at the park looking south]]
Amenities at the park include gardens, a nature center building, parking, bike racks, a children's playground, and {{convert|3.5|mi}} of gravel trails.<ref name="argus"/><ref name="prairies"/> The nature center, called the Nature House, is used for educational programs and includes rest rooms, plus is partly powered by [[solar panels]].<ref name="stumps"/><ref name="argus"/> Birds at the park include the Red-tailed Hawk, [[Great Horned Owl]], [[Bald Eagle]], Western Bluebird, several sparrow species, and the [[Olive-sided Flycatcher]].<ref name="stumps"/> Other animal species in the park include the [[Northern Red-legged Frog]], Western Gray Squirrel, Northern Alligator Lizard, and the [[Rubber Boa]].<ref name="stumps"/> Plant life includes [[Delphinium|''Delphinium leucophaeum'']], [[Oregon Sunshine]], [[Sidalcea|Meadow Checkermallow]], and [[Western Columbine]].<ref name="stumps"/>

